Corn Starch Cooking Tips: Use in place of flour as a thickener. Corn starch dissolves better than flour. If your gravy, sauce or soup recipe calls for flour, replace with half as much corn starch. Dissolve in cold water before adding to hot liquids. Mix corn starch with a little cold water until smooth, then gradually stir into hot liquid. Stir until it boils; boil one minute. Try one of two sauces for Chinese cooking. For stir-fry, add a mixture of corn starch, soy sauce or salt, vinegar and water at the last stage. For dishes cooked longer over low heat, thicken at the last minute with corn starch and water.

description:
Serve Kara-Age with Ponzu and Lime Ponzu. The citrus tang of Ponzu and the fresh lime flavor of Lime Ponzu accent the delicate ginger taste and crispiness of Kara-Age. Kara-Age (kah-rah ah-geh) is Japan's popular fried chicken dish, a standard appetizer. It also serves as a main course for lunch or dinner. Kara-Age has mouth-watering soy-ginger flavor, giving you moist, tender chicken nuggets with a delicately crunchy, flavorful exterior.

Directions
Get Ready: Cut 1-1/4 pounds boneless chicken thighs or breasts or fish fillets into 1-1/2 inch square pieces. Heat about 1/4 inch of vegetable oil in large, heavy skillet over Medium heat to 350 degrees F. Oil is ready when bread cube is dropped in oil and turns brown on the bottom in 20 seconds. To Shake and Pan-Fry: Pour 1 package Kikkoman Kara-Age mix in a large, plastic bag (not included) or pan. Moisten chicken or fish in water, allowing excess to drop off. Add dozen pieces at a time to bag or pan. Close top of bag and shake well or roll in pan to coat all pieces evenly. Discard any remaining coating mix. Pan-fry half of pieces in hot oil, 2 to 4 minutes, or until chicken or fish is cooked, turning pieces over frequently. Remove and drain on paper towels. Cook remaining pieces as directed. Makes 3-4 servings.
title: Kikkoman Karaage Soy-Ginger Seasoned Coating Mix - 2ct/6oz
